{"title_page": "Battle for Brest", "text_new": "{{About|the 1944 Battle for Brest in France|other uses|Battle of Brest (disambiguation){{!}}Battle of Brest}}\n{{more footnotes|date=January 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle for Brest\n|partof= [[Operation Overlord]], Battle of Normandy\n|image=battleforbrest.jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption= A US [[M18 Hellcat]] of the [[705th Tank Destroyer Battalion]] in the streets of [[Brest, France|Brest]] in September 1944\n|date=7 August \u2013 19 September 1944\n|place=[[Brittany]], [[France]]\n|coordinates={{coord|48|23|27|N|4|29|08|E|region:FR_source:kolossus-eswiki|display=inline}}\n|result=Allied victory\n|combatant1={{flag|United States|1912}}<br />{{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|combatant2={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany|name=Germany}}\n|commander1={{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[Troy H. Middleton]]<br />{{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[Walter M. Robertson]]<br />{{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[Donald A. Stroh]]<br />{{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[Charles H. Gerhardt]]\n|commander2={{flagicon|Nazi Germany}} [[Hermann-Bernhard Ramcke]]{{surrendered}}<br />{{flagicon|Nazi Germany}} [[Hans Kroh]]{{surrendered}}<br />{{flagicon|Nazi Germany}} [[Erwin Rauch]]{{surrendered}}\n|units1=[[VIII Corps (United States)|VIII Corps]]\n* [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]]\n* [[8th Infantry Division (United States)|8th Infantry Division]]\n* [[29th Infantry Division (United States)|29th Infantry Division]]\n* [[2nd Ranger Battalion (United States)|2nd Ranger Battalion]]\n* [[5th Ranger Battalion (United States)|5th Ranger Battalion]]\n* [[79th Armoured Division (United Kingdom)|79th Armoured Division]] (elements)\n* [[6th Armored Division (United States)|6th Armored Division]] (elements)\n|units2=[[2nd Parachute Division (Germany)|2nd Fallschirmj\u00e4ger-Division]]<br />[[266th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|266. Infanterie-Division]]<br />[[343rd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|343. Infanterie-Division]]\n|strength1=75,000 men\n|strength2=45,000 men\n|casualties1=9,831 killed or wounded{{sfn|Bllumenson|1961|p=653}}\n|casualties2=38,000 captured{{sfn|Bllumenson|1961|p=653}}\n|campaignbox={{Campaignbox Normandy}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle for Brest''' was fought on the [[Western Front (World War II)|Western Front]] during [[World War II]]. Part of the Allied plan for the [[Operation Overlord|invasion of mainland Europe]] called for the capture of port facilities, in order to ensure the timely delivery of the enormous amount of war [[wikt:materiel|materiel]] required to supply the invading Allied forces. It was estimated that the 37 Allied divisions to be on the continent by September 1944 would need 26,000 tons of supplies each day.<ref>{{Cite book|publisher =  |isbn =  0-8317-2188-X|last =  Kirkpatrick|first =  Charles|title =  D-Day: Operation Overlord: From the Landings at Normandy to the Liberation of Paris|url-access =  registration|url =  https://archive.org/details/ddayoperationove0000unse}}</ref> The main port the Allied forces hoped to seize and put into their service was [[Brest, France|Brest]], in northwestern France.\n\n==Background==\nEarly in the war, after the [[Battle of France|Fall of France]] in 1940, the United States and the United Kingdom began planning an eventual \"Invasion of Western Europe\" to be put into effect when and if the United States joined the war. American and Canadian troops would be moved from North America to England (as long as the United Kingdom was still in the war), until an Allied invasion could be mounted to the continent.\n\nA major issue was how to supply the invasion army with the tens of thousands of tons of materiel it would need after it landed. The capture of ports on the European Atlantic coast was a necessity, and the most suitable ones were clear invasion objectives. The capture of these port facilities was deemed crucial, because the lack of supplies would easily strand an invading army. For the initial phase of the battle, large artificial ports ([[Mulberry Harbour|Mulberry Harbors]]) would be erected on the beaches, but they had limited tonnage unloading capabilities, and were considered as a contingency until real ports could be captured and put into service.\n\nSuitable ports could be found along the northern coast of France, across the [[English Channel]] which would be crossed by the invading armies, in particular the port of Brest in [[Brittany]], for a long time the main French Fleet harbor on the Atlantic coast and the westernmost port in France. The Allied strategists even considered it possible that, after its capture, supplies could arrive directly from the US to Brest, bypassing England and reaching the Allied Armies moving east, towards Germany, much faster.\n\nOther ports across the English Channel were [[Saint Malo]], [[Lorient]], and [[Saint Nazaire]] in Brittany and [[Cherbourg]] and [[Le Havre]] in Normandy (which would eventually be selected as the Invasion area). [[Operation Sledgehammer]], the capture of Cherbourg, had been considered by the Allies, but it was cancelled after the disastrous 1942 [[Dieppe Raid]]. It was decided that a direct attack on a port from the sea was not an option.\n\nHowever, the Germans, realizing this, began building fortifications around these ports earlier in the war through their [[Organisation Todt|Organization Todt]], as part of the [[Atlantic Wall]] concept. Some of these ports were major [[U-boat]] bases as well, and had bomb-proof concrete submarine pens built. These fortifications had been surviving Allied air strikes for some time.\n\n==Prelude==\n[[File:approachtobrest.png|thumb|left|300px|NW France by mid-August, 1944. The Allies manage to occupy the Breton countryside and are already moving east towards Paris. The blue arrows represent the approach routes to Brest and other ports]]\nSoon after Normandy was invaded, the Mulberries were towed from England and deployed on the French coast. Unfortunately for the Allies, one of them was destroyed after less than two weeks. Supplies were then mainly landed directly via the beaches, but this process was not as efficient.\n\n[[Cherbourg-Octeville|Cherbourg]], at the tip of the [[Cotentin Peninsula]] in Normandy, was captured by the Americans who landed on [[Utah Beach]], but the German garrison destroyed its harbour facilities before surrendering. Cherbourg was the only major port in the Allied invasion area. Soon after, the Germans in the [[Brittany (peninsula)|Brittany]] [[peninsula]] were isolated by a north-south breakthrough accomplished by [[George S. Patton]]'s [[Third United States Army]], exploiting the success of [[Operation Cobra]]. The US VIII Corps was diverted into Brittany to capture Brest and secure the northern flank of the breakthrough. ''[[Wehrmacht]]'' troops trapped in Brittany retreated to the fortified ports in the peninsula, as US Third Army troops moved in and surrounded them. The Brest garrison, ''Festung Brest'', meaning \"Fortress Brest\", as German [[propaganda]] referred to surrounded cities, was put under the command of [[General (Germany)|General der Fallschirmtruppe]] [[Hermann-Bernhard Ramcke]], a paratroop veteran of the [[Afrika Korps]]. His forces consisted of the German [[2nd Parachute Division (Germany)|2nd Parachute Division]], [[266th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|266th Infantry Division]], [[343rd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|343rd Infantry Division]] and other ''Wehrmacht'' elements, in all some 40,000 fighting men.\n\nThe old fortress city of [[Saint-Malo]] was captured by the [[83rd Infantry Division (United States)|83rd Infantry Division]] (\"Ohio\") on 17 August, but its small port facilities were sabotaged by the defenders. A German garrison stationed at nearby [[C\u00e9zembre]] Island surrendered only after days of heavy shelling by warships and strong air strikes, when their naval guns were already disabled. The aerial bombing of the island marked one of the first uses of [[napalm]] bombs. It was clear that the Germans would deny the Allies the use of French ports as long as possible by defending the fortresses built around them and severely damaging their docks.\n\nBrest was reached by American troops on 7 August 1944.\n\n==Battle==\n[[File:Battle of Brittany - Brest 02.jpg|thumb|300px|Troops of the 2nd Infantry Division advance under machine gun fire into the outskirts of Brest]]\nBrest was surrounded and eventually stormed by the [[VIII Corps (United States)|U.S. VIII Corps]]. The fight proved extremely difficult, as the German garrison was well entrenched and partially made up of elite [[Fallschirmj\u00e4ger (World War II)|''Fallschirmj\u00e4ger'']] ([[paratrooper]]) forces.\n\nThe German paratroopers lived up to their reputation, as the Allies had experienced previously in battles such as [[Battle of Monte Cassino|Monte Cassino]]. Whilst some less capable units surrendered quite easily, the ''Fallschirmj\u00e4ger'' defended their ground under considerable odds, heavy shelling, air strikes and American assaults. The attackers had many losses inflicted on them for every small advance they made into the city.\n\nAs per their military doctrine, the Americans tried to use their superior artillery firepower and air superiority to overcome the defenders, instead of fighting them hand-to-hand. The Germans had stocked a considerable amount of ammunition for the defense of the city and had weapons of all calibers (from light [[flak]] to naval guns) dug into fortifications and in [[blockhouse|pillboxes]]. Elements of the specialised British [[79th Armoured Division (United Kingdom)|79th Armoured Division]] came in to attack the heavily fortified [[Fort Montbarey]]. Flamethrowing [[Churchill Crocodile]] tanks along with US infantry took three days to overcome the fort.\n\nThe fighting was intense, with the troops moving from [[urban warfare|house to house]]. The fortifications (both French and German built) proved very difficult to overcome, and heavy artillery barrages were fired by both sides.\n\nEventually the old city of Brest was razed to the ground during the battle, with only some medieval stone-built fortifications left standing.\n\nGeneral Ramcke surrendered the city on 19 September 1944 to the Americans after rendering the port facilities useless. These would not be repaired in time to help the war effort as it was hoped. By this time, [[Paris]] had already been liberated by the Allied Armies, and [[Operation Market-Garden]] was already under way in the Netherlands.\n\n===\"These Are My Credentials\"===\nWhen U.S. Brigadier General [[Charles D. W. Canham|Charles Canham]] arrived to accept Ramcke's surrender, the latter asked the lower-ranking man to show his credentials. Canham pointed to his nearby troops and said \"These are my credentials\". Canham was at the time the deputy commander of the [[8th Infantry Division (United States)|U.S. 8th Infantry Division]]; that phrase has since become the division's motto.\n\nThe costly capture of Brest resulted in the decision to only surround the remaining German-occupied ports in France with the exception of those that could be captured from the march, instead of storming them in a set-piece battle. The exception was Le Havre, which was taken by the [[British 2nd Army]] on 12 September 1944. Some of these Breton ports surrendered only by 9 May 1945, one day after [[Victory in Europe Day]].\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe whole Overlord campaign developed somewhat differently than originally planned. Patton's US Third Army's quick advance allowed the [[Liberation of Paris]] to occur earlier than expected, but by September 1944 supplies were beginning to run short.\n[[File:Fort Montbarey1.JPG|thumb|300px|Fort Montbary today with a [[Churchill Crocodile|Churchill 'Crocodile']]]]\n\nCherbourg was the only port that was repaired in time to be used and therefore by the end of the war in Europe despite the U.S. Army committing 75,000 troups to the capture of Brest of which 10,000 would become casualties, not a single Allied troop ship or supply vessel had docked in Brest <ref>{{Cite book|publisher = Stackpole Books|isbn = 9780811740500|last =  Balkoski|first = Joseph E.|title = From Beachhead to Brittany, The 29th Infantry Division at Brest, August-September 1944|page = xiii| year = 2008}}, [https://www.google.com/books/edition/From_Beachhead_to_Brittany/5iwZfCjS2GgC?hl=en&gbpv=0 partial text at Google Books]</ref>. The harbor's capacity was approximately 2,000 tons a day in mid-July and 12,000 tons by August 1944.\n\nA decision was made to favor the British forces under Sir [[Bernard Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery of Alamein|Bernard Montgomery]] by reducing the supplies to other forces, including Patton's. The unsuccessful Operation Market Garden launched by Montgomery soon after, however, did not allow the Allies to resume their rapid advance which was being stalled at [[Antwerp]] in Belgium.<ref>{{Cite book|publisher = University of British Columbia Press|isbn = 978-0-7748-2090-5|last =  Delaney|first = Douglas E.|title = Corps Commanders: Five British and Canadian Generals at War, 1939\u201345|page = 244|location = Vancouver BC| year = 2011}}</ref> The Germans were able to reorganize and even counterattack (e.g. the [[Battle of the Bulge]]). By then, however, Antwerp was secured, its port operating and supplying the Allies.\n\nAfter the war, the West German government paid reparations to civilians in Brest who had been killed, starved, or left homeless.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Portal|World War II}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat|Battle of Brittany}}\n* [[Joseph Balkoski]]. ''From Beachhead to Brittany: The 29th Infantry Division At Brest, August\u2013September 1944''. {{ISBN|0-8117-0325-8}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bllumenson|first1=Martin|title=Breakout and Pursuit|date=1961|publisher=Center of Military History|location=Washington, D.C.|url=https://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USA/USA-E-Breakout/index.html|ref=harv}}\n* Buchheim, L.G. ''Die Festung''. (literary treatment of the author's experiences as a German war reporter during the battle for France)\n* Dobler, Michael. ''Closing with the Enemy'', which contains a study of combat in Brest\n* Delaforce, Patrick. ''Churchill's Secret Weapons: The Story of Hobart's Funnies'',  Leo Cooper Ltd 2006 {{ISBN|978-1-84415-344-2}}\n* Gawne, Jonathan, ''The American in Brittany'', 1944, Histoire et Collections, Paris, France, 2002, {{ISBN|2-913903-21-5}}.\n* Kuby, E. ''Nur noch rauchende Tr\u00fcmmer''. (German \u2013 the author was an enlisted soldier in Brest). A radio play translated into English at erichkuby.info/Hoerspiel.pdf .\n* Jacques Pr\u00e9vert: [[:fr:Barbara (po\u00e8me)|\"Barbara\" (a poem) about the battle]]\n* Hitler's Sky Warriors by Christopher Ailsby\n\n{{World War II}}\n{{Battle of Normandy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brest, Battle For}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1944]]\n[[Category:1944 in France]]\n[[Category:History of Brest, France|Battle]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving France]]\n[[Category:Operation Overlord]]\n[[Category:Military history of France during World War II]]\n[[Category:Military operations of World War II involving Germany]]\n[[Category:Urban warfare]]\n[[Category:August 1944 events]]\n[[Category:September 1944 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1944 Battle for Brest in France|other uses|Battle of Brest (disambiguation){{!}}Battle of Brest}}\n{{more footnotes|date=January 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle for Brest\n|partof= [[Operation Overlord]], Battle of Normandy\n|image=battleforbrest.jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption= A US [[M18 Hellcat]] of the [[705th Tank Destroyer Battalion]] in the streets of [[Brest, France|Brest]] in September 1944\n|date=7 August \u2013 19 September 1944\n|place=[[Brittany]], [[France]]\n|coordinates={{coord|48|23|27|N|4|29|08|E|region:FR_source:kolossus-eswiki|display=inline}}\n|result=Allied victory\n|combatant1={{flag|United States|1912}}<br />{{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|combatant2={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany|name=Germany}}\n|commander1={{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[Troy H. Middleton]]<br/>{{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[Walter M. Robertson]]<br/>{{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[Donald A. Stroh]]<br/>{{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[Charles H. Gerhardt]]\n|commander2={{flagicon|Nazi Germany}} [[Hermann-Bernhard Ramcke]]{{surrendered}}<br/>{{flagicon|Nazi Germany}} [[Hans Kroh]]{{surrendered}}<br/>{{flagicon|Nazi Germany}} [[Erwin Rauch]]{{surrendered}}\n|units1=[[VIII Corps (United States)|VIII Corps]]\n* [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]]\n* [[8th Infantry Division (United States)|8th Infantry Division]]\n* [[29th Infantry Division (United States)|29th Infantry Division]]\n* [[2nd Ranger Battalion (United States)|2nd Ranger Battalion]]\n* [[5th Ranger Battalion (United States)|5th Ranger Battalion]]\n* [[79th Armoured Division (United Kingdom)|79th Armoured Division]] (elements)\n* [[6th Armored Division (United States)|6th Armored Division]] (elements)\n|units2=[[2nd Parachute Division (Germany)|2nd Fallschirmj\u00e4ger-Division]]<br />[[266th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|266. Infanterie-Division]]<br />[[343rd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|343. Infanterie-Division]]\n|strength1=75,000 men\n|strength2=45,000 men\n|casualties1=9,831 killed or wounded{{sfn|Bllumenson|1961|p=653}}\n|casualties2=38,000 captured{{sfn|Bllumenson|1961|p=653}}\n|campaignbox={{Campaignbox Normandy}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle for Brest''' was fought on the [[Western Front (World War II)|Western Front]] during [[World War II]]. Part of the Allied plan for the [[Operation Overlord|invasion of mainland Europe]] called for the capture of port facilities, in order to ensure the timely delivery of the enormous amount of war [[wikt:materiel|materiel]] required to supply the invading Allied forces. It was estimated that the 37 Allied divisions to be on the continent by September 1944 would need 26,000 tons of supplies each day.<ref>{{Cite book|publisher =  |isbn =  0-8317-2188-X|last =  Kirkpatrick|first =  Charles|title =  D-Day: Operation Overlord: From the Landings at Normandy to the Liberation of Paris|url-access =  registration|url =  https://archive.org/details/ddayoperationove0000unse}}</ref> The main port the Allied forces hoped to seize and put into their service was [[Brest, France|Brest]], in northwestern France.\n\n==Background==\nEarly in the war, after the [[Battle of France|Fall of France]] in 1940, the United States and the United Kingdom began planning an eventual \"Invasion of Western Europe\" to be put into effect when and if the United States joined the war. American and Canadian troops would be moved from North America to England (as long as the United Kingdom was still in the war), until an Allied invasion could be mounted to the continent.\n\nA major issue was how to supply the invasion army with the tens of thousands of tons of materiel it would need after it landed. The capture of ports on the European Atlantic coast was a necessity, and the most suitable ones were clear invasion objectives. The capture of these port facilities was deemed crucial, because the lack of supplies would easily strand an invading army. For the initial phase of the battle, large artificial ports ([[Mulberry Harbour|Mulberry Harbors]]) would be erected on the beaches, but they had limited tonnage unloading capabilities, and were considered as a contingency until real ports could be captured and put into service.\n\nSuitable ports could be found along the northern coast of France, across the [[English Channel]] which would be crossed by the invading armies, in particular the port of Brest in [[Brittany]], for a long time the main French Fleet harbor on the Atlantic coast and the westernmost port in France. The Allied strategists even considered it possible that, after its capture, supplies could arrive directly from the US to Brest, bypassing England and reaching the Allied Armies moving east, towards Germany, much faster.\n\nOther ports across the English Channel were [[Saint Malo]], [[Lorient]], and [[Saint Nazaire]] in Brittany and [[Cherbourg]] and [[Le Havre]] in Normandy (which would eventually be selected as the Invasion area). [[Operation Sledgehammer]], the capture of Cherbourg, had been considered by the Allies, but it was cancelled after the disastrous 1942 [[Dieppe Raid]]. It was decided that a direct attack on a port from the sea was not an option.\n\nHowever, the Germans, realizing this, began building fortifications around these ports earlier in the war through their [[Organisation Todt|Organization Todt]], as part of the [[Atlantic Wall]] concept. Some of these ports were major [[U-boat]] bases as well, and had bomb-proof concrete submarine pens built. These fortifications had been surviving Allied air strikes for some time.\n\n==Prelude==\n[[File:approachtobrest.png|thumb|left|300px|NW France by mid-August, 1944. The Allies manage to occupy the Breton countryside and are already moving east towards Paris. The blue arrows represent the approach routes to Brest and other ports]]\nSoon after Normandy was invaded, the Mulberries were towed from England and deployed on the French coast. Unfortunately for the Allies, one of them was destroyed after less than two weeks. Supplies were then mainly landed directly via the beaches, but this process was not as efficient.\n\n[[Cherbourg-Octeville|Cherbourg]], at the tip of the [[Cotentin Peninsula]] in Normandy, was captured by the Americans who landed on [[Utah Beach]], but the German garrison destroyed its harbour facilities before surrendering. Cherbourg was the only major port in the Allied invasion area. Soon after, the Germans in the [[Brittany (peninsula)|Brittany]] [[peninsula]] were isolated by a north-south breakthrough accomplished by [[George S. Patton]]'s [[Third United States Army]], exploiting the success of [[Operation Cobra]]. The US VIII Corps was diverted into Brittany to capture Brest and secure the northern flank of the breakthrough. ''[[Wehrmacht]]'' troops trapped in Brittany retreated to the fortified ports in the peninsula, as US Third Army troops moved in and surrounded them. The Brest garrison, ''Festung Brest'', meaning \"Fortress Brest\", as German [[propaganda]] referred to surrounded cities, was put under the command of [[General (Germany)|General der Fallschirmtruppe]] [[Hermann-Bernhard Ramcke]], a paratroop veteran of the [[Afrika Korps]]. His forces consisted of the German [[2nd Parachute Division (Germany)|2nd Parachute Division]], [[266th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|266th Infantry Division]], [[343rd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|343rd Infantry Division]] and other ''Wehrmacht'' elements, in all some 40,000 fighting men.\n\nThe old fortress city of [[Saint-Malo]] was captured by the [[83rd Infantry Division (United States)|83rd Infantry Division]] (\"Ohio\") on 17 August, but its small port facilities were sabotaged by the defenders. A German garrison stationed at nearby [[C\u00e9zembre]] Island surrendered only after days of heavy shelling by warships and strong air strikes, when their naval guns were already disabled. The aerial bombing of the island marked one of the first uses of [[napalm]] bombs. It was clear that the Germans would deny the Allies the use of French ports as long as possible by defending the fortresses built around them and severely damaging their docks.\n\nBrest was reached by American troops on 7 August 1944.\n\n==Battle==\n[[File:Battle of Brittany - Brest 02.jpg|thumb|300px|Troops of the 2nd Infantry Division advance under machine gun fire into the outskirts of Brest]]\nBrest was surrounded and eventually stormed by the [[VIII Corps (United States)|U.S. VIII Corps]]. The fight proved extremely difficult, as the German garrison was well entrenched and partially made up of elite [[Fallschirmj\u00e4ger (World War II)|''Fallschirmj\u00e4ger'']] ([[paratrooper]]) forces.\n\nThe German paratroopers lived up to their reputation, as the Allies had experienced previously in battles such as [[Battle of Monte Cassino|Monte Cassino]]. Whilst some less capable units surrendered quite easily, the ''Fallschirmj\u00e4ger'' defended their ground under considerable odds, heavy shelling, air strikes and American assaults. The attackers had many losses inflicted on them for every small advance they made into the city.\n\nAs per their military doctrine, the Americans tried to use their superior artillery firepower and air superiority to overcome the defenders, instead of fighting them hand-to-hand. The Germans had stocked a considerable amount of ammunition for the defense of the city and had weapons of all calibers (from light [[flak]] to naval guns) dug into fortifications and in [[blockhouse|pillboxes]]. Elements of the specialised British [[79th Armoured Division (United Kingdom)|79th Armoured Division]] came in to attack the heavily fortified [[Fort Montbarey]]. Flamethrowing [[Churchill Crocodile]] tanks along with US infantry took three days to overcome the fort.\n\nThe fighting was intense, with the troops moving from [[urban warfare|house to house]]. The fortifications (both French and German built) proved very difficult to overcome, and heavy artillery barrages were fired by both sides.\n\nEventually the old city of Brest was razed to the ground during the battle, with only some medieval stone-built fortifications left standing.\n\nGeneral Ramcke surrendered the city on 19 September 1944 to the Americans after rendering the port facilities useless. These would not be repaired in time to help the war effort as it was hoped. By this time, [[Paris]] had already been liberated by the Allied Armies, and [[Operation Market-Garden]] was already under way in the Netherlands.\n\n===\"These Are My Credentials\"===\nWhen U.S. Brigadier General [[Charles D. W. Canham|Charles Canham]] arrived to accept Ramcke's surrender, the latter asked the lower-ranking man to show his credentials. Canham pointed to his nearby troops and said \"These are my credentials\". Canham was at the time the deputy commander of the [[8th Infantry Division (United States)|U.S. 8th Infantry Division]]; that phrase has since become the division's motto.\n\nThe costly capture of Brest resulted in the decision to only surround the remaining German-occupied ports in France with the exception of those that could be captured from the march, instead of storming them in a set-piece battle. The exception was Le Havre, which was taken by the [[British 2nd Army]] on 12 September 1944. Some of these Breton ports surrendered only by 9 May 1945, one day after [[Victory in Europe Day]].\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe whole Overlord campaign developed somewhat differently than originally planned. Patton's US Third Army's quick advance allowed the [[Liberation of Paris]] to occur earlier than expected, but by September 1944 supplies were beginning to run short.\n[[File:Fort Montbarey1.JPG|thumb|300px|Fort Montbary today with a [[Churchill Crocodile|Churchill 'Crocodile']]]]\n\nCherbourg was the only port that was repaired in time to be used and therefore by the end of the war in Europe despite the U.S. Army committing 75,000 troups to the capture of Brest of which 10,000 would become casualties, not a single Allied troop ship or supply vessel had docked in Brest <ref>{{Cite book|publisher = Stackpole Books|isbn = 9780811740500|last =  Balkoski|first = Joseph E.|title = From Beachhead to Brittany, The 29th Infantry Division at Brest, August-September 1944|page = xiii| year = 2008}}, [https://www.google.com/books/edition/From_Beachhead_to_Brittany/5iwZfCjS2GgC?hl=en&gbpv=0 partial text at Google Books]</ref>. The harbor's capacity was approximately 2,000 tons a day in mid-July and 12,000 tons by August 1944.\n\nA decision was made to favor the British forces under Sir [[Bernard Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery of Alamein|Bernard Montgomery]] by reducing the supplies to other forces, including Patton's. The unsuccessful Operation Market Garden launched by Montgomery soon after, however, did not allow the Allies to resume their rapid advance which was being stalled at [[Antwerp]] in Belgium.<ref>{{Cite book|publisher = University of British Columbia Press|isbn = 978-0-7748-2090-5|last =  Delaney|first = Douglas E.|title = Corps Commanders: Five British and Canadian Generals at War, 1939\u201345|page = 244|location = Vancouver BC| year = 2011}}</ref> The Germans were able to reorganize and even counterattack (e.g. the [[Battle of the Bulge]]). By then, however, Antwerp was secured, its port operating and supplying the Allies.\n\nAfter the war, the West German government paid reparations to civilians in Brest who had been killed, starved, or left homeless.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Portal|World War II}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat|Battle of Brittany}}\n* [[Joseph Balkoski]]. ''From Beachhead to Brittany: The 29th Infantry Division At Brest, August\u2013September 1944''. {{ISBN|0-8117-0325-8}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bllumenson|first1=Martin|title=Breakout and Pursuit|date=1961|publisher=Center of Military History|location=Washington, D.C.|url=https://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USA/USA-E-Breakout/index.html|ref=harv}}\n* Buchheim, L.G. ''Die Festung''. (literary treatment of the author's experiences as a German war reporter during the battle for France)\n* Dobler, Michael. ''Closing with the Enemy'', which contains a study of combat in Brest\n* Delaforce, Patrick. ''Churchill's Secret Weapons: The Story of Hobart's Funnies'',  Leo Cooper Ltd 2006 {{ISBN|978-1-84415-344-2}}\n* Gawne, Jonathan, ''The American in Brittany'', 1944, Histoire et Collections, Paris, France, 2002, {{ISBN|2-913903-21-5}}.\n* Kuby, E. ''Nur noch rauchende Tr\u00fcmmer''. (German \u2013 the author was an enlisted soldier in Brest). A radio play translated into English at erichkuby.info/Hoerspiel.pdf .\n* Jacques Pr\u00e9vert: [[:fr:Barbara_(po\u00e8me)|\"Barbara\" (a poem) about the battle]]\n*Hitler's Sky Warriors by Christopher Ailsby\n\n{{World War II}}\n{{Battle of Normandy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brest, Battle For}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1944]]\n[[Category:1944 in France]]\n[[Category:History of Brest, France|Battle]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving France]]\n[[Category:Operation Overlord]]\n[[Category:Military history of France during World War II]]\n[[Category:Military operations of World War II involving Germany]]\n[[Category:Urban warfare]]\n[[Category:August 1944 events]]\n[[Category:September 1944 events]]\n", "name_user": "Eastfarthingan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_for_Brest"}
{"title_page": "Olga Hudlick\u00e1", "text_new": "{{short description|Czech-born English physiologist (1926\u20132014)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Olga Hudlick\u00e1\n| image         = Olga_Hudlick\u00e1.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = 1990 award ceremony photograph\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1926|07|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[P\u0159elou\u010d]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2014|05|03|1926|07|11|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Birmingham]], [[England]]\n| nationality   = Czech / British\n| other_names   = Olga Hudlicka, Olga Klein-Hudlicka\n| occupation    = scientist, academic\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = studying vascular development and muscle blood flow\n| notable_works = ''Angiogenesis'', 1986\n}}\n\n'''Olga Hudlick\u00e1''' (11 July 1926 \u2013 3 May 2014) was a Czech-born [[physiologist]], who fled the [[Normalization (Czechoslovakia)|normalization of communism]] in her country and moved to England. Working at the [[University of Birmingham]], she studied blood flow and [[Ischemia|restriction]], as well as capillary growth in [[cardiac muscle|cardiac]] and [[skeletal muscle]]s. \n\n==Early life==\nOlga Hudlick\u00e1 was born on 11 July 1926 [[P\u0159elou\u010d]], [[Czechoslovakia]] to Marie (n\u00e9e Babackova) and Jaroslav Hudlick\u00fd.<ref name= \"Coote\">{{Cite news|last=Coote|first=John H.|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/jul/15/olga-hudlicka|title=Olga Hudlick\u00e1 obituary|date=2014-07-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723075659/https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/jul/15/olga-hudlicka|archive-date=2016-07-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Her mother worked as a clerk and her father was an engineer in P\u0159elou\u010d. Hudlick\u00e1 began her schooling in [[Olomouc]]  and then completed her secondary education in [[Prague]].<ref name=\"Kost\">{{cite book | last=\u0160trb\u00e1\u0148ov\u00e1 | first=So\u0148a | title=Sto \u010desk\u00fdch v\u011bdc\u016f v exilu : encyklopedie v\u00fdznamn\u00fdch v\u011bdc\u016f z \u0159ad pracovn\u00edk\u016f \u010ceskoslovensk\u00e9 akademie v\u011bd v emigraci | publisher=Academia | publication-place=Praha | year=2011 | isbn=978-80-200-1915-8 | oclc=734000235 | language=sk | pages=281\u2013283}}</ref> During her schooling, the [[German occupation of Czechoslovakia|Nazis invaded and occupied]] her homeland.<ref name=\"Coote\" /> After completing her mandatory work brigades, she finished high school in 1945.<ref name=\"Kost\" /> When [[World War II]] ended, Hudlick\u00e1 began her medical studies at [[Charles University]], earning her medical degree in 1950.<ref name=\"Coote\" /><ref name=\"Brown1\">{{cite journal | last=Egginton | first=Stuart | last2=Brown | first2=Margaret D. | title=In Memoriam: Olga Hudlick\u00e1 (11.07.26-03.05.14) | journal=Microcirculation | publisher=Wiley | volume=21 | issue=6 | year=2014 | issn=1073-9688 | doi=10.1111/micc.12151 | pages=475\u2013477}}</ref>{{rp|475}} That same year, she married a physician who worked at Prague's main hospital, Andrei Klein.<ref name=\"Coote\" /> \n\nHudlick\u00e1 continued her education at the {{ill|Institute of Physiology of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic|lt=Institute of Physiology of the Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences|cs|Fyziologick\u00fd \u00fastav Akademie v\u011bd \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky}} ({{lang-cs|Fyziologick\u00fd \u00fastav (FG\u00da)}}), inspired to study muscle blood flow by the work of Ernest Gutmann. Completing her PhD in 1954, she was invited to work in the Pharmacology Department at the [[Karolinska Institute]] of [[Stockholm]] in 1960. That same year, she became the honorary secretary of the Czechoslovak Physiological Society. In 1964, she was again invited to study abroad and took a position at [[Duke University Medical Center]] in [[Durham, North Carolina]]. After completing her [[Doctor of Science]] degree in 1968 at FG\u00da, she returned to Duke to study in the laboratory of Gene Renkin. Despite the [[Cold War]], the liberalization during the [[Prague Spring]] allowed her obtain permission for the additional studies and to attend the International Congress of Physiological Sciences, held that year in [[Washington, D. C.]].<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|475}}\n\nBy the time that Hudlick\u00e1 returned to Czechoslovakia, just before Christmas, the period of liberalization was over and the [[USSR]] had [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia|brought in tanks]] to suppress the Czechoslovak government. In spite of the return to authoritarianism, Hudlick\u00e1 was allowed to present a paper at [[Oxford]]'s [[Physiological Society]] in the summer of 1969. While they were in England, she and her husband made plans to evacuate their family from Czechoslovakia. Soon after their return to the country, on the pretense of a holiday visit with friends, they flew their son to [[London]] and sent their daughter to [[Colmar]] in northern France. With the children securely out of the country, Hudlick\u00e1 and Klein packed a small suitcase and drove to visit friends in [[Hungary]].<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|475}} From Hungary, the couple drove on to France to meet their daughter, via [[Austria]] and [[Italy]].<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}} In [[Paris]], they were reunited with their son and the family made their way to [[Z\u00fcrich]], [[Switzerland]], where they met Hudlick\u00e1's mother and put her on a plane to USA for a visit with Hudlick\u00e1's older brother while the family decided where to settle..<ref name=\"Coote\" /><ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}} Their escape occurred just before the Czechoslovakian borders were closed on 15 September 1969.<ref name=\"Coote\" />\n\n==Career==\nHudlick\u00e1 obtained work at the [[Max Planck Institute]],<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}} but by the end of the year, she and her children moved to England as she had accepted an invitation to join the department of physiology of [[Birmingham University]].<ref name=\"Coote\" /> By February 1970, her husband and mother were reunited with the family. Klein began working at a hospital in Birmingham, while Hudlick\u00e1 resumed her interest in blood flow.<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}} She published a monograph in 1973, ''Muscle Blood Flow'', which was followed by ''Angiogenesis'' in 1986.<ref name=\"Coote\" /> This work was influential in its investigation of capillary growth in cardiac and skeletal muscles. Evaluating the mechanisms that regulate blood flow and the process by which [[Angiogenesis|new blood vessels form]], Hudlick\u00e1 recognized that by indirectly using electrical stimulation on skeletal muscles, one could alter the mechanisms which deliver oxygen and nutrients to muscles. The therapeutic implications for patients included resistance to fatigue and increased blood flow, similar to that obtained by exercise training, for patients afflicted with heart failure, hypertension, or stroke. Hudlick\u00e1 authored or co-authored over 200 publications, edited and reviewed works for such publications as ''Microcirculation'', and trained doctoral students. She served as honorary secretary of the British Microcirculation Society between 1985 and 1992 and as its president from 1996 to 1999.<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}}\n\nHudlick\u00e1 served as a visiting professor at many international universities, including the [[Central University of Venezuela]] in [[Caracas]], the [[University of California, Davis|University of California at Davis]], and the [[University of Frankfurt am Main]]. She was the recipient of numerous awards, including delivering the [[The Physiological Society#Annual Review Prize Lecture|Annual Review Lecture of the Physiological Society]] in 1990;<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}} the Benjamin W. Zweifach Award of the [[Microcirculatory Society]] in 1996;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.microcirc.org/site_page.cfm?pk_association_webpage_menu=2208&pk_association_webpage=5883|title=Benjamin W. Zweifach Award|last=|first=|date=|website=www.microcirc.org|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316091135/http://www.microcirc.org/site_page.cfm?pk_association_webpage_menu=2208&pk_association_webpage=5883|archive-date=2016-03-16}}</ref> and the Malpighi Award of the European Society for\nMicrocirculation in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.szote.u-szeged.hu/esm/index.php/news-events/30-obituary-professor-olga-hudlicka|title=Obituary: Professor Olga Hudlicka|last=Koller|first=Akos|date=|website=www2.szote.u-szeged.hu|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512234907/http://www3.szote.u-szeged.hu/esm/index.php/news-events/30-obituary-professor-olga-hudlicka|archive-date=2015-05-12}}</ref>\n\nAfter her retirement in 1993, Hudlick\u00e1 continued working as a professor emeritus<ref name=\"Coote\" /> and continued practicing in surgery and conducting research.<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|477}}  Among works she published were ''Application of Muscle/Nerve Stimulation in Health and Disease'' in 2008<ref name=\"Coote\" /> and several [[cookbooks]] detailing recipes to treat specific types of ailments and disease.<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|477}}\n\n==Death and legacy==\nHudlick\u00e1 died on 3 May, 2014, after a fall.<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|477}} Her work on the mechanisms regulating the growth of capillaries, how cancerous tumors are invaded by blood vessels and new blood vessels are formed, provided fundamental understanding of \nmuscle performance and therapeutic approaches which can be used to alleviate vascular disease.<ref name=\"Coote\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hudlicka, Olga}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovak people]]\n[[Category:Women physiologists]]\n[[Category:Women scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Czech women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Czech women writers]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Birmingham]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Czech-born English physiologist (1926\u20132014)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Olga Hudlick\u00e1\n| image         = Olga_Hudlick\u00e1.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = 1990 award ceremony photograph\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1926|07|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[P\u0159elou\u010d]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2014|05|03|1926|07|11|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Birmingham]], [[England]]\n| nationality   = Czech / British\n| other_names   = Olga Hudlicka, Olga Klein-Hudlicka\n| occupation    = scientist, academic\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = studying vascular development and muscle blood flow\n| notable_works = ''Angiogenesis'', 1986\n}}\n\n'''Olga Hudlick\u00e1''' (11 July 1926 \u2013 3 May 2014) was a Czech-born [[physiologist]], who fled the [[Normalization (Czechoslovakia)|normalization of communism]] in her country and moved to England. Working at the [[University of Birmingham]], she studied blood flow and [[Ischemia|restriction]], as well as capillary growth in [[cardiac muscle|cardiac]] and [[skeletal muscle]]s. \n\n==Early life==\nOlga Hudlick\u00e1 was born on 11 July 1926 [[P\u0159elou\u010d]], [[Czechoslovakia]] to Marie (n\u00e9e Babackova) and Jaroslav Hudlick\u00fd.<ref name= \"Coote\">{{Cite news|last=Coote|first=John H.|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/jul/15/olga-hudlicka|title=Olga Hudlick\u00e1 obituary|date=2014-07-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723075659/https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/jul/15/olga-hudlicka|archive-date=2016-07-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Her mother worked as a clerk and her father was an engineer in P\u0159elou\u010d. Hudlick\u00e1 began her schooling in [[Olomouc]]  and then completed her secondary education in [[Prague]].<ref name=\"Kost\">{{cite book | last=\u0160trb\u00e1\u0148ov\u00e1 | first=So\u0148a | title=Sto \u010desk\u00fdch v\u011bdc\u016f v exilu : encyklopedie v\u00fdznamn\u00fdch v\u011bdc\u016f z \u0159ad pracovn\u00edk\u016f \u010ceskoslovensk\u00e9 akademie v\u011bd v emigraci | publisher=Academia | publication-place=Praha | year=2011 | isbn=978-80-200-1915-8 | oclc=734000235 | language=sk | pages=281\u2013283}}</ref> During her schooling, the [[German occupation of Czechoslovakia|Nazis invaded and occupied]] her homeland.<ref name=\"Coote\" /> After completing her mandatory work brigades, she finished high school in 1945.<ref name=\"Kost\" /> When [[World War II]] ended, Hudlick\u00e1 began her medical studies at [[Charles University]], earning her medical degree in 1950.<ref name=\"Coote\" /><ref name=\"Brown1\">{{cite journal | last=Egginton | first=Stuart | last2=Brown | first2=Margaret D. | title=In Memoriam: Olga Hudlick\u00e1 (11.07.26-03.05.14) | journal=Microcirculation | publisher=Wiley | volume=21 | issue=6 | year=2014 | issn=1073-9688 | doi=10.1111/micc.12151 | pages=475\u2013477}}</ref>{{rp|475}} That same year, she married a physician who worked at Prague's main hospital, Andrei Klein.<ref name=\"Coote\" /> \n\nHudlick\u00e1 continued her education at the {{ill|Institute of Physiology of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic|lt=Institute of Physiology of the Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences|cs|Fyziologick\u00fd \u00fastav Akademie v\u011bd \u010cesk\u00e9 republiky}} ({{lang-cs|Fyziologick\u00fd \u00fastav (FG\u00da)}}), inspired to study muscle blood flow by the work of Ernest Gutmann. Completing her PhD in 1954, she was invited to work in the Pharmacology Department at the [[Karolinska Institute]] of [[Stockholm]] in 1960. That same year, she became the honorary secretary of the Czechoslovak Physiological Society. In 1964, she was again invited to study abroad and took a position at [[Duke University Medical Center]] in [[Durham, North Carolina]]. After completing her [[Doctor of Science]] degree in 1968 at FG\u00da, she returned to Duke to study in the laboratory of Gene Renkin. Despite the [[Cold War]], the liberalization during the [[Prague Spring]] allowed her obtain permission for the additional studies and to attend the International Congress of Physiological Sciences, held that year in [[Washington, D. C.]].<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|475}}\n\nBy the time that Hudlick\u00e1 returned to Czechoslovakia, just before Christmas, the period of liberalization was over and the [[USSR]] had [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia|brought in tanks]] to suppress the Czechoslovak government. In spite of the return to authoritarianism, Hudlick\u00e1 was allowed to present a paper at [[Oxford]]'s [[Physiological Society]] in the summer of 1969. While they were in England, she and her husband made plans to evacuate their family from Czechoslovakia. Soon after their return to the country, on the pretense of a holiday visit with friends, they flew their son to [[London]] and sent their daughter to [[Colmar]] in northern France. With the children securely out of the country, Hudlick\u00e1 and Klein packed a small suitcase and drove to visit friends in [[Hungary]].<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|475}} From Hungary, the couple drove on to France to meet their daughter, via [[Austria]] and [[Italy]].<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}} In [[Paris]], they were reunited with their son and the family made their way to [[Z\u00fcrich]], [[Switzerland]], where they met Hudlick\u00e1's mother and put her on a plane to USA for a visit with Hudlick\u00e1's older brother while the family decided where to settle..<ref name=\"Coote\" /><ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}} Their escape occurred just before the Czechoslovakian borders were closed on 15 September 1969.<ref name=\"Coote\" />\n\n==Career==\nHudlick\u00e1 obtained work at the [[Max Planck Institute]],<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}} but by the end of the year, she and her children moved to England as she had accepted an invitation to join the department of physiology of [[Birmingham University]].<ref name=\"Coote\" /> By February 1970, her husband and mother were reunited with the family. Klein began working at a hospital in Birmingham, while Hudlick\u00e1 resumed her interest in blood flow.<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}} She published a monograph in 1973, ''Muscle Blood Flow'', which was followed by ''Angiogenesis'' in 1986.<ref name=\"Coote\" /> This work was influential in its investigation of capillary growth in cardiac and skeletal muscles. Evaluating the mechanisms that regulate blood flow and the process by which [[Angiogenesis|new blood vessels form]], Hudlick\u00e1 recognized that by indirectly using electrical stimulation on skeletal muscles, one could alter the mechanisms which deliver oxygen and nutrients to muscles. The therapeutic implications for patients included resistance to fatigue and increased blood flow, similar to that obtained by exercise training, for patients afflicted with heart failure, hypertension, or stroke. Hudlick\u00e1 authored or co-authored over 200 publications, edited and reviewed works for such publications as ''Microcirculation'', and trained doctoral students. She served as honorary secretary of the British Microcirculation Society between 1985 and 1992 and as its president from 1996 to 1999.<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}}\n\nHudlick\u00e1 served as a visiting professor at many international universities, including the [[Central University of Venezuela]] in [[Caracas]], the [[University of California, Davis|University of California at Davis]], and the [[University of Frankfurt am Main]]. She was the recipient of numerous awards, including delivering the [[The Physiological Society#Annual Review Prize Lecture|Annual Review Lecture of the Physiological Society]] in 1990;<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|476}} the Benjamin W. Zweifach Award of the [[Microcirculatory Society]] in 1996;{{sfn|Microcirculatory Society|2016}} and the Malpighi Award of the European Society for\nMicrocirculation in 2008.{{sfn|Koller|2014}}\n\nAfter her retirement in 1993, Hudlick\u00e1 continued working as a professor emeritus<ref name=\"Coote\" /> and continued practicing in surgery and conducting research.<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|477}}  Among works she published were ''Application of Muscle/Nerve Stimulation in Health and Disease'' in 2008<ref name=\"Coote\" /> and several [[cookbooks]] detailing recipes to treat specific types of ailments and disease.<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|477}}\n\n==Death and legacy==\nHudlick\u00e1 died on 3 May, 2014, after a fall.<ref name=\"Brown1\" />{{rp|477}} Her work on the mechanisms regulating the growth of capillaries, how cancerous tumors are invaded by blood vessels and new blood vessels are formed, provided fundamental understanding of \nmuscle performance and therapeutic approaches which can be used to alleviate vascular disease.<ref name=\"Coote\" />\n\n== References ==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite news|ref=harv|last1=Coote|first1=John H.|title=Olga Hudlick\u00e1 obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/jul/15/olga-hudlicka|accessdate=13 April 2017|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=15 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723075659/https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/jul/15/olga-hudlicka|archivedate=23 July 2016|location=London, England|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite journal|ref=harv|last1=Egginton|first1=Stuart|last2=Brown|first2=Margaret D.|title=In Memoriam:  Olga Hudlick\u00e1 (11.07.26 \u2013 03.05.14)|journal=Microcirculation|date=August 2014|volume=21|issue=6|pages=475\u2013477|doi=10.1111/micc.12151|url=http://web.b.ebscohost.com/ehost/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?sid=8b41e494-7283-430f-8ebf-53eb5ccfc7c7%40sessionmgr101&vid=0&hid=116|accessdate=13 April 2017|publisher=John Wiley & Sons Ltd.|location=Hoboken, New Jersey|issn=1549-8719}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]